{
  "According to the Hardy-Weinberg principle, allele frequencies in a population remain constant when:": "",
  "Organisms only reproduce asexually": "",
  "Natural selection is strongly favoring one allele": "",
  "There is no mutation, selection, migration, genetic drift, or non-random mating": "",
  "The population is very small": "",
  "Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium requires five conditions: no mutation, random mating, no natural selection, an infinitely large population (no genetic drift), and no gene flow. When all conditions are met, allele and genotype frequencies remain constant.": "",
  "In the Hardy-Weinberg equation p² + 2pq + q² = 1, what does 2pq represent?": "",
  "The frequency of heterozygous individuals": "",
  "The frequency of homozygous recessive individuals": "",
  "The frequency of homozygous dominant individuals": "",
  "The total allele frequency in the population": "",
  "In the Hardy-Weinberg equation, p² represents homozygous dominant frequency, q² represents homozygous recessive frequency, and 2pq represents the frequency of heterozygous individuals in the population.": "",
  "If the frequency of the recessive allele (q) in a population is 0.3, what is the frequency of the dominant allele (p)?": "",
  "0.49": "",
  "0.3": "",
  "0.7": "",
  "0.09": "",
  "Since p + q = 1, if q = 0.3, then p = 1 - 0.3 = 0.7. This equation reflects that the two allele frequencies for a two-allele system must sum to 1 (100% of alleles in the gene pool).": "",
  "A population is in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium for a particular gene. Which of the following must be true?": "",
  "The dominant allele is increasing in frequency": "",
  "The population is evolving rapidly": "",
  "All individuals are homozygous for the gene": "",
  "The population is not evolving at this gene locus": "",
  "Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium means allele and genotype frequencies are not changing, which is the definition of a non-evolving population. It serves as a null model against which real populations are compared to detect evolution.": "",
  "Which condition would cause a population to deviate from Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium?": "",
  "Absence of migration into or out of the population": "",
  "Random mating within the population": "",
  "Non-random mating, such as assortative mating": "",
  "A very large population size": "",
  "Non-random mating, such as preferential mating with similar phenotypes (assortative mating), violates one of the Hardy-Weinberg conditions and can change genotype frequencies, causing the population to deviate from equilibrium.": "",
  "In a population of 1000 individuals, 160 show the recessive phenotype (aa). What is the frequency of the recessive allele (q)?": "",
  "0.4": "",
  "0.16": "",
  "0.6": "",
  "0.84": "",
  "The frequency of the recessive phenotype (q²) = 160/1000 = 0.16. Taking the square root: q = sqrt(0.16) = 0.4. Therefore, the frequency of the recessive allele is 0.4.": "",
  "The equation p + q = 1 represents:": "",
  "The rate of mutation in a gene": "",
  "The sum of all allele frequencies for a two-allele gene must equal one": "",
  "The total number of individuals in a population": "",
  "The ratio of males to females in a population": "",
  "For a gene with two alleles, p represents the frequency of one allele and q represents the frequency of the other. Since these are the only two alleles, their frequencies must sum to 1, representing 100% of the gene pool.": "",
  "A gene pool is defined as:": "",
  "The number of genes on a chromosome": "",
  "All the alleles for all genes in a population at a given time": "",
  "A collection of genes from different species": "",
  "The total DNA of a single organism": "",
  "A gene pool is the complete set of alleles for all genes in all individuals of a population. Changes in the gene pool (allele frequency changes) over time constitute evolution at the population level.": "",
  "If a population is in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium with p = 0.6 and q = 0.4, what percentage of the population is expected to be heterozygous?": "",
  "48%": "",
  "36%": "",
  "16%": "",
  "24%": "",
  "The frequency of heterozygous individuals is 2pq = 2(0.6)(0.4) = 0.48, or 48%. This is the expected proportion of heterozygous individuals under Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium.": "",
  "Why is the Hardy-Weinberg model useful even though natural populations rarely meet all its conditions?": "",
  "It provides a null hypothesis for detecting evolutionary change in populations": "",
  "It proves that evolution does not occur": "",
  "It accurately describes all natural populations": "",
  "It eliminates the need for field research": "",
  "Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium serves as a null model. By comparing observed allele and genotype frequencies to expected equilibrium values, scientists can detect when evolution is occurring and investigate which mechanisms are responsible.": "",
  "What is 'allele frequency'?": "",
  "The number of different genes in an organism": "",
  "The number of alleles in a single organism's genome": "",
  "The proportion of a specific allele relative to all alleles for that gene in a population": "",
  "The rate at which new alleles arise through mutation": "",
  "Allele frequency is the relative abundance of a particular allele at a genetic locus in a population, expressed as a proportion or percentage. Changes in allele frequencies over time define microevolution.": "",
  "What does 'Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium' mean?": "",
  "A state in which all organisms in a population are genetically identical": "",
  "A balance between the number of males and females in a population": "",
  "A condition where the population size remains constant over time": "",
  "A state in which a population's allele and genotype frequencies remain constant from generation to generation in the absence of evolutionary forces": "",
  "Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium is a theoretical state where allele and genotype frequencies do not change across generations, indicating no evolution. It requires no mutation, random mating, no selection, infinite population size, and no migration.": "",
  "What does 'gene pool' mean?": "",
  "The set of genes unique to one individual": "",
  "A pool of water where genetic material is stored": "",
  "The total collection of all alleles for all genes present in a population at a given time": "",
  "The genes found only in reproductive cells": "",
  "The gene pool encompasses all alleles at all gene loci in every individual of a population. It is the genetic resource from which the next generation is drawn, and changes in the gene pool represent evolution.": "",
  "What is 'genotype frequency'?": "",
  "The total number of genes in an organism's genome": "",
  "The speed at which genotypes change in a population": "",
  "The proportion of individuals in a population with a specific genotype": "",
  "The number of different genotypes that exist in all species": "",
  "Genotype frequency is the fraction of individuals in a population that carry a specific genotype (e.g., AA, Aa, or aa). Under Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, genotype frequencies can be predicted from allele frequencies using p², 2pq, and q².": "",
  "What does 'microevolution' mean?": "",
  "Changes in allele frequencies within a population over generations": "",
  "Evolution that occurs only in microorganisms": "",
  "Evolution that can only be observed under a microscope": "",
  "The formation of new species through geographic isolation": "",
  "Microevolution refers to changes in allele frequencies within a population over successive generations. It is the smallest scale of evolution and can result from natural selection, genetic drift, mutation, or gene flow.": "",
  "What is 'random mating'?": "",
  "Mating only between unrelated individuals": "",
  "Mating that produces random numbers of offspring": "",
  "Mating that occurs at random times during the year": "",
  "Mating in which individuals pair by chance, with no preference for particular genotypes or phenotypes": "",
  "Random mating (panmixia) means every individual has an equal probability of mating with any other individual regardless of genotype. It is a requirement for Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium and ensures genotype frequencies match expected proportions.": "",
  "What does 'assortative mating' mean?": "",
  "A form of non-random mating in which individuals tend to mate with others that are phenotypically similar (positive) or dissimilar (negative)": "",
  "The random pairing of individuals regardless of their traits": "",
  "Mating between individuals of different species": "",
  "Artificial breeding programs designed by humans": "",
  "Assortative mating is a form of non-random mating. Positive assortative mating (like mates with like) increases homozygosity, while negative assortative mating (opposites attract) increases heterozygosity, both altering genotype frequencies.": "",
  "What is 'genetic variation'?": "",
  "The process of DNA replication": "",
  "The differences in DNA sequences among individuals within a population": "",
  "The physical appearance of an organism": "",
  "The movement of genes between populations": "",
  "Genetic variation refers to the diversity of alleles and genotypes within a population. It is the raw material for evolution, arising through mutation, sexual reproduction, and gene flow, and is essential for natural selection to operate.": "",
  "What does 'heterozygote advantage' mean?": "",
  "A situation where heterozygous individuals have greater fitness than either homozygous genotype, maintaining both alleles in the population": "",
  "The benefit of having more chromosomes than other organisms": "",
  "Heterozygous individuals always produce more offspring than any other genotype": "",
  "The advantage of having two different species interbreed": "",
  "Heterozygote advantage (overdominance) occurs when heterozygous individuals have higher fitness than either homozygote. The classic example is sickle cell trait: heterozygotes resist malaria better than either homozygote, maintaining both alleles.": "",
  "What does 'population' mean in genetics?": "",
  "All living organisms on Earth": "",
  "The total number of species in an ecosystem": "",
  "Any group of organisms living in the same habitat regardless of species": "",
  "A group of individuals of the same species that live in the same area and can interbreed": "",
  "In population genetics, a population is a group of individuals of the same species living in the same area that actually or potentially interbreed. The population is the unit in which microevolution occurs.": "",
  "In a population of 500 people, 20 individuals have sickle cell disease (homozygous recessive, ss). Assuming Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, approximately how many people are carriers (heterozygous, Ss)?": "",
  "About 320 people": "",
  "About 40 people": "",
  "About 160 people": "",
  "About 250 people": "",
  "q² = 20/500 = 0.04, so q = 0.2 and p = 0.8. The carrier frequency (2pq) = 2(0.8)(0.2) = 0.32. In 500 people: 0.32 x 500 = 160 carriers. Hardy-Weinberg calculations reveal that carriers are much more common than affected individuals.": "",
  "A population geneticist samples a population of wildflowers and finds that the observed genotype frequencies differ significantly from Hardy-Weinberg expectations, with far more homozygotes than predicted. Which of the following is the most likely explanation?": "",
  "The population is experiencing high rates of random mating": "",
  "Gene flow from nearby populations is introducing new alleles": "",
  "Inbreeding or positive assortative mating is occurring, increasing homozygosity beyond Hardy-Weinberg predictions": "",
  "The mutation rate is unusually high": "",
  "An excess of homozygotes relative to Hardy-Weinberg expectations is a hallmark of non-random mating, specifically inbreeding or positive assortative mating, where like genotypes preferentially mate together.": "",
  "In a region of Africa where malaria is prevalent, the frequency of the sickle cell allele (HbS) is about 0.12, much higher than in populations without malaria. Scientists hypothesize that heterozygote advantage maintains this allele. Which prediction would support this hypothesis?": "",
  "Heterozygous individuals (HbA/HbS) should have higher survival and reproductive success than both homozygous genotypes in malaria-endemic areas": "",
  "The HbS allele frequency should continue to increase until all individuals are homozygous HbS": "",
  "Homozygous HbS individuals should have the highest fitness": "",
  "The HbS allele should be equally common in populations with and without malaria": "",
  "Heterozygote advantage (balancing selection) predicts that heterozygotes have the highest fitness. HbA/HbS heterozygotes resist malaria (unlike HbA/HbA) and avoid severe sickle cell disease (unlike HbS/HbS), maintaining both alleles at stable frequencies in malaria regions.": "",
  "A researcher compares allele frequencies at a particular locus in a population over five generations and finds no significant change. She concludes the population is in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium. Another scientist argues this conclusion may be premature. Why?": "",
  "Multiple evolutionary forces could be acting in opposing directions, keeping allele frequencies stable even though the population is not in true equilibrium": "",
  "Five generations is too many for meaningful comparison": "",
  "Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium can only be tested with one generation of data": "",
  "Allele frequencies can never remain stable for five generations": "",
  "Stable allele frequencies alone do not prove Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium. Opposing forces (e.g., selection favoring one allele while migration introduces the other) could balance each other, producing stable frequencies even though evolutionary forces are actively operating.": "",
  "In a population of 10,000 individuals, 9% show a recessive phenotype. After a new predator is introduced that preferentially targets individuals with the recessive phenotype, the frequency of the recessive phenotype drops to 1% over several generations. How has the allele frequency changed?": "",
  "q increased because predators always increase allele frequencies": "",
  "q decreased from 0.3 to 0.1, showing natural selection reduced the frequency of the recessive allele": "",
  "q remained at 0.3 because selection only affects phenotypes, not alleles": "",
  "p decreased from 0.7 to 0.1 because predators target dominant individuals": "",
  "Initially, q² = 0.09, so q = 0.3. After selection, q² = 0.01, so q = 0.1. The recessive allele frequency decreased from 0.3 to 0.1 because individuals expressing the recessive phenotype were selectively removed from the population by predation.": "",
  "A medical geneticist notes that cystic fibrosis (autosomal recessive) affects about 1 in 2500 Caucasian newborns. Using Hardy-Weinberg, she calculates the carrier frequency. Why is this information clinically important?": "",
  "It proves that cystic fibrosis will eventually be eliminated from the population": "",
  "It shows that all Caucasians carry the cystic fibrosis allele": "",
  "It helps determine the frequency of carriers (about 1 in 25) who may unknowingly pass the allele to their children": "",
  "It indicates that cystic fibrosis is not a genetic disorder": "",
  "If q² = 1/2500, then q = 1/50 and p = 49/50. Carrier frequency (2pq) is approximately 2(49/50)(1/50) = about 1/25 or 4%. This reveals that carriers are 100 times more common than affected individuals, important for genetic counseling.": "",
  "Two neighboring populations of the same butterfly species are separated by a river. Population A has an allele frequency of p = 0.8 for wing color, while Population B has p = 0.3. A bridge is built across the river, and extensive interbreeding occurs. After several generations, both populations have p = 0.6. What does this demonstrate?": "",
  "Gene flow through migration and interbreeding homogenized allele frequencies between the two populations": "",
  "Mutation independently produced the same allele frequency in both populations": "",
  "Genetic drift randomly caused both populations to converge on the same frequency": "",
  "Natural selection favored p = 0.6 in both populations": "",
  "Gene flow between the two populations through interbreeding mixed their gene pools, causing allele frequencies to converge toward an intermediate value. This demonstrates how gene flow reduces genetic differences between connected populations.": "",
  "A conservation biologist is managing a small, endangered population of 50 wolves. She is concerned about genetic drift and inbreeding. Which management strategy would best address both concerns?": "",
  "Introduce wolves from a different, genetically diverse population to increase gene flow and genetic diversity": "",
  "Reduce the population further to only the fittest individuals": "",
  "Prevent any wolves from leaving or entering the population": "",
  "Allow only the largest males to breed": "",
  "Introducing individuals from other populations creates gene flow, which increases genetic diversity, reduces inbreeding, and counteracts the harmful effects of genetic drift in small populations. This strategy is called genetic rescue.": "",
  "A student samples a population and calculates the observed genotype frequencies as: AA = 0.64, Aa = 0.16, aa = 0.20. The expected Hardy-Weinberg frequencies based on allele frequencies would be AA = 0.5184, Aa = 0.4032, aa = 0.0784. What conclusion can the student draw?": "",
  "The population is not in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium; the excess of homozygotes and deficit of heterozygotes suggests non-random mating such as inbreeding": "",
  "The population has too many heterozygotes, suggesting outbreeding": "",
  "The population is in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium": "",
  "The data are insufficient to draw any conclusions": "",
  "The observed frequencies show more homozygotes and fewer heterozygotes than expected under Hardy-Weinberg. This pattern is characteristic of inbreeding or positive assortative mating, both of which increase homozygosity at the expense of heterozygosity.": "",
  "In a lab experiment, a researcher starts with 100 populations of fruit flies, each containing 10 flies with identical initial allele frequencies (p = q = 0.5) for eye color. After 20 generations with no selection, the researcher finds that some populations have lost the red allele entirely, others have lost the brown allele, and others still have both. What explains this outcome?": "",
  "Mutation rates differed between populations, creating different allele frequencies": "",
  "Genetic drift caused random changes in allele frequencies in these small populations, leading to fixation or loss of alleles in some": "",
  "Natural selection acted differently in each population": "",
  "Gene flow between populations caused the observed differences": "",
  "With no selection acting, the only evolutionary force operating in these small, isolated populations is genetic drift. Random sampling each generation causes allele frequencies to fluctuate unpredictably, eventually leading to fixation or loss of alleles, especially in populations as small as 10 individuals.": ""
}